<DOC><DOCNO> AP890111-0006 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0030EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Armenia-Nuclear     01-11 0130</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Armenia-Nuclear,0135</SECOND><HEAD>Soviets To Close Armenian Nuke Plant By March</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nuclear power plant in an earthquake-prone areaof Soviet Armenia will be closed by March, Soviet televisionreported.   The Vremya evening news program reported Tuesday night that oneof the plant's reactors would shut down by Feb. 25, the second byMarch 18.   The plant, located in the Armenian capital of Yerevan, was notdamaged by the devastating Dec. 7 earthquake in another part of thesmall southern Soviet republic that borders Turkey.   But officials began to take environmentalists' concern over theplant's hazardous location more seriously after that quake, whichkilled at least 25,000 people.   Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov said in December that the plant wouldclose within two years due to the earthquake danger.</TEXT></DOC>